The inductive hypothesis is the assumption that P(k)P(k)P(k)P(k) is true for some kkkk.

Assume P(k)P(k)P(k)P(k) is true for some kkkk. That is, we assume that the following equation is true:

1^2+2^2+3^2+\cdots+k^2=\frac{k(k+1)(2k+1)}{6}
12+22+32+⋯+k2=k(k+1)(2k+1)61^2+2^2+3^2+\cdots+k^2=\frac{k(k+1)(2k+1)}{6} 12+22+32+⋯+k2=6k(k+1)(2k+1)​

The "left-hand side" of P(k+1)P(k+1)P(k+1)P(k+1) is 1^2+2^2+3^2+\cdots +k^2 + (k+1)^212+22+32+⋯+k2+(k+1)21^2+2^2+3^2+\cdots +k^2 + (k+1)^212+22+32+⋯+k2+(k+1)2. But by our assumption (here we use the inductive hypothesis), the first kkkk terms are equal to \frac{k(k+1)(2k+1)}{6}k(k+1)(2k+1)6\frac{k(k+1)(2k+1)}{6}6k(k+1)(2k+1)​ so we can re-write:

\begin{align*}

12+22+⋯+k2+(k+1)2=k(k+1)(2k+1)6+(k+1)2=k(k+1)(2k+1)+6(k+1)26=(k+1)(k(2k+1)+6(k+1))6=(k+1)(k+2)(2k+3)6=(k+1)(k+2)(2(k+1)+1)6\begin{align*} 1^2+2^2+\cdots +k^2 + (k+1)^2 &= \frac{k(k+1)(2k+1)}{6} + (k+1)^2 \\ &= \frac{k(k+1)(2k+1)+6(k+1)^2}{6}\\ &= \frac{(k+1)(k(2k+1)+6(k+1))}{6}\\ &= \frac{(k+1)(k+2)(2k+3)}{6}\\ &= \frac{(k+1)(k+2)(2(k+1)+1)}{6}\\ \end{align*} 12+22+⋯+k2+(k+1)2​=6k(k+1)(2k+1)​+(k+1)2=6k(k+1)(2k+1)+6(k+1)2​=6(k+1)(k(2k+1)+6(k+1))​=6(k+1)(k+2)(2k+3)​=6(k+1)(k+2)(2(k+1)+1)​​

In total, we have shown that if P(k)P(k)P(k)P(k) is true, then 1^2+2^2+\cdots +k^2 + (k+1)^2 = \frac{(k+1)(k+2)(2(k+1)+1)}{6}12+22+⋯+k2+(k+1)2=(k+1)(k+2)(2(k+1)+1)61^2+2^2+\cdots +k^2 + (k+1)^2 = \frac{(k+1)(k+2)(2(k+1)+1)}{6}12+22+⋯+k2+(k+1)2=6(k+1)(k+2)(2(k+1)+1)​, but this is just P(k+1)P(k+1)P(k+1)P(k+1) so we have completed the induction step as we have shown that P(k)\implies P(k+1)P(k)  ⟹  P(k+1)P(k)\implies P(k+1)P(k)⟹P(k+1).

You can do the exact same argument with bbbb instead of aaaa to complete this step. Try it, and try to understand every little step in the reasoning.

In (d), we showed that cccc is a common divisor of aaaa and bbbb. And in (c), we showed that if there is another common divisor dddd of aaaa and bbbb, then c\mid dc∣dc\mid dc∣d so d\leq cd≤cd\leq cd≤c. Therefore, cccc is the greatest common divisor of aaaa and bbbb. \begin{align*}

&=(f(n-2)-1)-1 = f(n-2)-2\\
&= (f(n-3) - 1)-2 = f(n-3)-3\\
&= (f(n-4) - 1)-3 = f(n-4)-4\\
&\vdots\\
&= f(n-n) - n = f(0) - n = 1-n
\end{align*}
f(n)=f(n−1)−1=(f(n−2)−1)−1=f(n−2)−2=(f(n−3)−1)−2=f(n−3)−3=(f(n−4)−1)−3=f(n−4)−4⋮=f(n−n)−n=f(0)−n=1−n\begin{align*} f(n)&=f(n-1)-1\\ &=(f(n-2)-1)-1 = f(n-2)-2\\ &= (f(n-3) - 1)-2 = f(n-3)-3\\ &= (f(n-4) - 1)-3 = f(n-4)-4\\ &\vdots\\ &= f(n-n) - n = f(0) - n = 1-n \end{align*} f(n)​=f(n−1)−1=(f(n−2)−1)−1=f(n−2)−2=(f(n−3)−1)−2=f(n−3)−3=(f(n−4)−1)−3=f(n−4)−4⋮=f(n−n)−n=f(0)−n=1−n​

So f(n) = 1-nf(n)=1−nf(n) = 1-nf(n)=1−n. We can test this formula for f(n-1) - 1 = (1-(n-1)) - 1 = 1-n+1-1 = 1-n = f(n)f(n−1)−1=(1−(n−1))−1=1−n+1−1=1−n=f(n)f(n-1) - 1 = (1-(n-1)) - 1 = 1-n+1-1 = 1-n = f(n)f(n−1)−1=(1−(n−1))−1=1−n+1−1=1−n=f(n).

a) Let P(n) : n\equiv 1\pmod 4P(n):n≡1(mod4)P(n) : n\equiv 1\pmod 4P(n):n≡1(mod4). We want to show that P(n)P(n)P(n)P(n) is true for all n\in Sn∈Sn\in Sn∈S.

Induction step: Assume P(k)P(k)P(k)P(k) is true. We want to show that this implies that P(k+1)P(k+1)P(k+1)P(k+1) is true.

P(k) : k\equiv 1\pmod 4P(k):k≡1(mod4)P(k) : k\equiv 1\pmod 4P(k):k≡1(mod4) so k=4\cdot m + 1k=4⋅m+1k=4\cdot m + 1k=4⋅m+1 for some integer mmmm.

Then, we check that k^2k2k^2k2 satisfy PPPP:

One of these are to show that prime factorization is unique (up to order of multiplication). This is a nice exercise.

For the sake of contradiction, assume there are two different prime factorization of an integer nnnn:

n=p_1 p_2 \cdots p_n = q_1 q_2\cdots q_m
n=p1p2⋯pn=q1q2⋯qmn=p_1 p_2 \cdots p_n = q_1 q_2\cdots q_m n=p1​p2​⋯pn​=q1​q2​⋯qm​

for primes p_1, p_2, \ldots, p_np1,p2,…,pnp_1, p_2, \ldots, p_np1​,p2​,…,pn​ and q_1, q_2, \ldots, q_mq1,q2,…,qmq_1, q_2, \ldots, q_mq1​,q2​,…,qm​.

Use the following lemma:
If n\mid abn∣abn\mid abn∣ab and \gcd(n,a)=1gcd⁡(n,a)=1\gcd(n,a)=1gcd(n,a)=1 then n\mid bn∣bn\mid bn∣b.

Special case of the above lemma (why is this true?):
If p\mid abp∣abp\mid abp∣ab and pppp is prime, then p\mid ap∣ap\mid ap∣a or p\mid bp∣bp\mid bp∣b.

We clearly have that p_1\mid np1∣np_1\mid np1​∣n, so p_1\mid q_1q_2\cdots q_mp1∣q1q2⋯qmp_1\mid q_1q_2\cdots q_mp1​∣q1​q2​⋯qm​ and by the special case of our lemma p_1p1p_1p1​ divides at least one of the q_jqjq_jqj​. Since p_1p1p_1p1​ and q_jqjq_jqj​ are prime, we must have p_1=q_jp1=qjp_1=q_jp1​=qj​ for some jjjj. Without loss of generality, we can assume that j=1j=1j=1j=1.

Now, divide nnnn by p_1p1p_1p1​ and repeat the argument for p_2p2p_2p2​ until we are left with only p_npnp_npn​ and q_mqmq_mqm​.
